-- 
Singapore Stocks: Noble Group, Olam, Sembcorp Marine, Sinomem

-- B y   J o n a t h a n   B u r g o s
-- 
2011-03-22T01:16:50Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-21/k-reit-asia-sembcorp-marine-sinomem-singapore-stocks-preview.html
Singapore’s  Straits Times Index (FSSTI)  was
little changed at 2,984.03 as of 9:10 a.m. local time. About
three stocks advanced for every two that fell in the benchmark
index of 30 companies advanced.  Shares on the measure trade at an average 13.7 times
estimated earnings, compared with about 15.6 times at the end of
2010, according to data compiled by Bloomberg.  The following shares were among the most active in the
market. Stock symbols are in parentheses after the company name.  Commodity suppliers: The Thomson Reuters/Jefferies CRB
Index, which tracks prices of 19 commodities from copper to
corn, gained 0.6 percent in  New York  yesterday, extending its
advance for a fourth day.  Noble Group Ltd. (NOBL)  , a Hong Kong-based supplier of
commodities, increased 1 percent to S$2.09.  Olam International
Ltd. (OLAM)  , a Singapore-based supplier of agricultural
commodities, rose 0.4 percent to S$2.60.  Sembcorp Marine Ltd. (SMM)  , the world’s second-biggest
builder of oil platforms, gained 0.7 percent to S$5.52. The
company said it received an order valued at $450 million for the
construction of a jack-up drilling rig for Seadrill Ltd.  Sinomem Technology Ltd. (SINO)  , the maker of water-
filtration membranes used in pharmaceutical, food and water-
treatment industries, rose 0.7 percent to 68.5 Singapore cents.
The company said it dispatched Clean Water Investment Ltd.’s
offer document to its shareholders. Clean Water’s offer to buy
all of Sinomem’s shares will close on April 19, according to the
document.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Jonathan Burgos in  Singapore  at 
 jburgos4@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Gentle at   ngentle2@bloomberg.net . 